Finally watched it (the movie just recently became available here in Germany). I was kind of primed to hate it from what I'd been hearing, but actually found myself enjoying the first half hour or so quite a lot. The goofiness of the first action scene stayed squarely in Donner territory and thankfully never quite crossed the line into Lester-land, and I felt the movie was getting a lot right about Wonder Woman's character while having a lot of fun with her. I liked Barbara Minerva's character, even though she was kind of a familiar superhero movie villain trope and I enjoyed Pedro Pascal as Max Lord.  So I started to feel maybe I'd been misled and this movie was kind of awesome ... But then it started going downhill really quickly. I would've forgiven the problematic return of Steve Trevor if that was all that was wrong with this movie, but there was so much more that broke my enjoyment of it. The plot just fell apart like a Jenga tower and some of the action was just laughably badly staged, which was a real surprise after the first movie and the first couple of scenes of this one. I feel sorry for the cast, because they were all pretty awesome. Gal Gadot remains a brilliant choice to play Wonder Woman, I enjoyed seeing Chris Pine back in this (even if his return was really badly plotted) and Kristen Wiig and Pascal both did a great job with some lame material. Considering that Patty Jenkins has been saying in interviews that this was her own true vision, without any interference from the studio, this is really disappointing. And honestly, I think the studio's public commitment to keeping her on for the next Wonder Woman movie now looks like a mistake.

Personally, I would've:
1) Made Hades the villain, which means no Dreamstone with all its convoluted mechanics. Hades simply comes to Diana and offers to revive Steve in exchange for her godly status and powers.
2) As you said, make the fact the Diana loses her powers the central point of the film. Like, she makes the deal and she immediately wakes up next to Steve (who's in HIS body) and without her powers. And she has to actually experience life as a human for a good portion of the film, like Peter Parker in Spider-Man 2. It would've been doubly interesting for Diana, because her story is all about a goddess understanding humanity. The first movie was about her having a first glimpse of our nature, but still from her position of superiority. This one could've been her actually experiencing human life as one of us.

I didn‚Äôt like this movie, but I think the monkey‚Äôs paw thing _isn‚Äôt_ used as an alibi for lazy writing here. When they are flying in the invisible jet and fireworks appear and it‚Äôs 4 July suddenly‚Äîthat is an alibi and excuse so they could have an invisible plane fly through some fireworks. The monkey‚Äôs paw, though, is _not_ used like that. The entire movie is about cheating, lying and, ultimately, egoism on a supernatural scale that threatens to destroy our species. Diana‚Äôs attempt to cheat at the beginning of the movie is somewhat innocent and forgivable, especially for a kid. But it only seems that way. If everyone did that to get what they want, what kind of world would it be? Reminds of me Kant. We see that play out in the movie. The entire planet begins wishing and wishing, gaining what they want without working towards it, without _achieving_ it through will and action. Diana indulges her desire to be with a dead man; she herself begins to weaken and die the longer she is with him. To live with him means to live with the dead. They talk about the truth a lot, too, and this also makes sense. Getting what you wish for instantaneously makes your reality a lie. There is no truth when your wish is granted. You didn‚Äôt work for it, didn‚Äôt earn it, didn‚Äôt sacrifice time and energy to make it come true‚Äîcome _true._ Instead of accepting her loss and learning to live without her beloved, Diana gives up her reality for a delusion. You can see how this plays out in the other characters, too. I‚Äôm not defending the movie, only the claim that they were using the monkey‚Äôs paw purely for its convenience. I enjoy the abstraction of what this movie could have been. It was poorly realized‚Äîbut there are hints of it. For instance, the clearly intended tonal shift from cartoonish violence to sexual assault to nuclear annihilation.

Well, I don't get all the backlash the movie received so far. Some troubles here and there as always happen in the industry. The movie isn't perfect, it's far from being an action packed one as you and most of the people have wished for a sequel, but is not that bad as you and a lot of reviewers make it seems. I've watched your review when you posted it, but I waited to watch the movie before writing a comment. I did watch it just now. And my conclusion is that men and women are so used to watch action movies made by men and for men that we (me included) are always expecting what the male industry can offer without even notice that. Patty Jenkins did a great job once again in terms of giving to the audience a different perspective of what an action movie about a female hero could be. The movie has a warm honesty, full of soul and emotion. It's not heartless. Wonder Woman is all over it, because it's not just about the character and her powers, but what she does mean inside all the archetypes she dresses. I loved the way Barbra was introduced, even though we've seen it before a thousand times. Loved the way story brought Steve back and how blind Diana became after that and also how she was neglecting her future by trapping herself in a past she idealized, like a teenage that thinks life is meaningless after the loss of a big first love. Although a goddess, she's human after all, and she still has a lot to learn from life and relationships of all sorts. I have my negative points about the movie as well as I have about the first one and I will not point any because people are doing it so much that they completely forgot that the sense of criticism is not about that only, and the movie has a lot more to offer than the flaws people are pitching. And just remembering that "the rock" is a stone created by a god for the purpose of creating caos when giving a desired wish in exchange of what one has and preserves the most, and of course the story would surrounds it, the same way as Tolkien makes it to a ring.

I honestly don't understand the hatred for the movie. I was someone who refused to see it on the grounds that from what I had heard, it had strong far-leftist, feminist and anti-male agenda - that's how people made it sound, like Maxwell Lord was a dancing "orange man bad" character. I didn't expect to like the film -so I waited until I watched it online. I was wrong. It was better than I expected, and it really did not busy itself with any social agenda or identity politics. Well. For the MOST part - there was some diversity pandering present (see below). 

The issues I had with it were not non-existent, however:
1. The film begins in her homeland, which is CLEARLY meant to be based very closely on Greek mythology and therefore very similar to Greece and Italy in terms of population and climate. But in the opening sequence, you do see a bunch of black Amazons. My problem with this is that it willfully ignores the fact that the native population of Greece is NOT black, no matter how many migrants have been trying to sneak in lately. The ancient, original population did not consist of very dark skinned sub-saharan Africans. That's just a fact. Greeks are European and as such, LOOK European. TO put this another way, it's like if you had a film set in ancient China - say, Mulan - or a land closely based on ancient China - and in among the Chinese warriors there's a sprinkling of black people. It wouldn't make SENSE given the geography and demographics native to the region, and it REEKS of diversity quotas: someone thought it would be a good idea to inject other ethnicities in there just to have them there without thinking about the reality of the world (ironic, given the film tells people to accept reality and don't try to make things what they are not). I get that Themascara is NOT a real place, so there's SOME artistic flexibility there, but let's be honest - if you went to ancient Greece - which is where Themascara is very clearly based on- you would not find a bunch of blacks running around. Sorry. Accept reality, as the film says. The shots in AMERICA that have a diverse population are FINE - I have no problem with that. That's REALITY. America is a highly diverse country. But ancient Greece had a pretty homogeneous population who would look more or less like the indigenous population of today - "white" with Mediterranean features. Gal Gadot herself is not Greek, but she LOOKS closer to it, being Israeli, than a Sub-Saharan African. This is too common place in hollywood and it is not necessary. You don't ALWAYS need token black or asian people in every setting just as I don't expect to see a blonde haired, blue eyed Swedish guy looking like Pewdiepie running around in a film set in ancient China. It wouldn't FIT. You can get outraged and call that racism or  you could...again...accept reality. 

2. The film ends with ALL wishes being undone, which I find exceedingly unlikely if literally millions to billions  had made a wish. I cannot see EVERYONE undoing their wish. Furthermore, when the wishes are undone, things like nuclear missiles disappear and people come back from the dead - yet, the place is still a complete mess when Lord comes out of the building and sees his son. First...how the hell did his son happen to find his way there, and second...if everything else was undone, why's there trash and rubble everywhere? I suppose by Lord himself undoing HIS wish he would take back the wishes of anyone who had made one and had it granted whether they wanted to or not, but this would kind of ignore the point of people having to willingly relinquish their wishes. 

3. Why isn't Maxwell Lord in prison after this? That part I can't understand. He was literally plastering his face all over the planet and a lot of chaos would pretty quickly be attributed to him - yet if you go by the film's ending, he gets to just walk away into obscurity with his son and live happily ever after. 

4. As a geologist, the language Wigg uses when trying to talk like one is pretty silly and laughable and shows a lack of understanding on the part of the writer...which indicates a lack of research being conducted. Something I resent as a writer. Many films do this - the new Ghostbusters trailer does the same thing "there's not a tectonic plate within miles" (uh...you're literally standing on one no matter WHERE you go) and they expect nobody to notice.  

5. The man whose body Steve Trevor inhabits was essentially raped by Wonder Woman. What do I mean? Well....he had his body - without his permission - inhabited by Steve Trevor, who proceeds to have - it's pretty obvious - sex with Diana. Which means this guy who Steve is inhabiting had his penis put into the body of a woman he did not know without his permission. That's rape. Mind you....I don't think most straight men on the planet would COMPLAIN if they got to have sex with Gal Gadot but my point remains. Wonder Woman raped a guy. She literally raped a guy. Rape is by definition sexual intercourse without the consent of the other party  - and as he did not give his consent to have his body used for that purpose, he was raped. Let me put this in the reverse way in case there's any confusion because there seems to be a bias against men and a mental block people have against the notion that a man can be violated: 
Imagine that Superman lost Lois Lane. Lois then comes back to life in the sense that her spirit is in the body of another woman who did not have a say in the matter. KNOWING this, Superman proceeds to have a passionate night with "Lois" and has sex with her in that woman's body. Question: when that woman gets her body back, is it not true that Superman TECHNICALLY has been inside of her, without her consent, knowingly? Don't you suppose audiences would pick up on that a lot faster if the genders were reversed? I think they would. They'd call it sexist. But if it happens to a man it's fine, somehow. Gotcha.

I, for one, found the theme to be quite interesting. It's not just "be careful what you wish for", it's also "face the truth". You could easily nitpick at it, but for Diana, it's not just that she's losing her strength when Steve comes back, it's that she has to accept that he's dead, and also that her wish is stealing somebody else's life. Steve even says it a couple times in the movie. He feels bad for the dude he's taken the body of.
It's not just that your taking a shortcut might get you something bad in return, it's that it can get somebody else something bad in return too. That's what you have with the opening sequence: not only has Diana cheated, but she would have stolen the winning spot from the one who did not cheat.
Similarly, when the dude wishes that woman to die on the spot, he's clearly doing it in a state of anger. Would he still be happy with the result later on, when he's cooled down? and are there people who would not want that woman to die because they depend on her and/or love her? etc.
As I said, you could nitpick "what about a kid with cancer", but that's the truth of life too. Sometimes, it's unfair, and it sucks, but that's how it is. Maybe your kid getting better means another kid dies. And if your kid is the one getting better, you don't care, but if you are the one with the kid dying in its stead, you won't be so happy.

In my opinion, the same soul but different body thing is a problem, not just because Diana had sex with him, but also because we are not even seeing the same guy our main protagonist is seeing, therefore creating differing, but clashing points of view between the audiences and the film's main protagonist. So, when Diana was renouncing her wish, it is not as powerful as the film is making it up to be in my opinion, since (again) we are not seeing the same guy Diana sees. Because how could we even connect emotionally with the main protagonist, if he/she has differing points of view that clashes with the audiences‚Äô perspective? This storytelling technique may work in different movies with different scenes with different contexts, particularly used for comedic effect, but in this case (and in my opinion), it did not.

NOT QUITE A "HEAVEN CAN'T WAIT" RETURN
Movie writers  doesn't always cater to every moviegoer's likes and dislikes pertaining to how they wanted the direction of the film's story is going, and writers are free to set the rules they want for the premise of their story they're trying to convey to work, and then they just have to cross their fingers and hope the movie's audience are intelligent enough to understand the narrative they're trying to tell.  As for this particular divisive movie, in as much as half of its audience prefer to rather have Steve come back fully (body & soul) in the most conventional & convenient way avoiding controversy (the issue of without-consent body swapping), we on the contrary prefer the filmmakers' bold choice of having him back this twisted way‚Äîunconventional, inconvenient & not clich√©.  Quite original we might say, albeit very contentious understandably.  All for that pivotal heartbreaking letting-you-go moment of Steve and Diana.  That scene wouldn't have worked the way that it did if the storytellers went the easy way...

     DIANA: "I can't say goodbye...I can't say goodbye..."
     STEVE: "You don't have to...I'm already gone."

Those lines would have been not impactful at all if they did it differently...And NO, we don't want an AVENGERS: INFINITY WAR all over again, where we see a fully-resurrected Steve Trevor fade away or poofed out of existence‚Äîthat would have been a far worse awful thing than the "disastrous cringey twist" haters of the movie are nitpicking!  It's vital for the movie to show that Diana needs to face the TRUTH that Steve has long been gone from her life, that she's kidding herself if she intends to keep Steve in this most unusual way‚Äîthat things should go back to its proper order especially for that Lyle Waggoner-looking "handsome guy" who she‚Äîout of being forlorn for the longest time‚Äîunintentionally used conveniently like a crutch to heal her broken heart. Wonder Woman is essentially a figure that was created to inspire courage, strength, nobility and honour. This is what made the original such a strong genre movie, Patty Jenkins nailed the essence of the character in a very good way and Diana‚Äôs fictional universe felt three-dimensional. 
There were stakes, lessons, challenges, mystery, sacrifice and triumph. 

Fast forward to 1984 and sadly all the merits of the original that made it - memorable, definitive and competent, are completely absent. The script is hollow, no real meat to it, the movie has a running time that is 30 minutes too long! There‚Äôs literally no stakes, continuity lacks consistency (Diana loses her powers one minute, then she uses them the next). Barbara and Max are woefully underdeveloped. 
Their arcs are filled to the brim with every cheesy-villain cliche in the book it‚Äôs hilarious! ü§£üòÇüòÜü§¶üèø‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è

There is also no real crisis in this movie; the point when the world is in disarray due to everyone making a wish, is absolute cringe. Things become even more cartoonish and silly. Wonder Woman flying in the sky like she‚Äôs getting a massage killed it! üòÇüòáüòÖ The suspension of disbelief was clearly void here. 

This movie is basically a love story: the central theme that consists of (having what you want but at a huge cost, then realising that you can‚Äôt have the thing you most desire, you just have accept it and be grateful) is badly executed here. The underlying message is easily absorbed but lacks convincing.

Apparently patty actually wrote this movie, I think she should just stick to directing next time, her strong suit. I don‚Äôt often like to compare movies even if they are sequels because I consider every movie for what it is, but i couldn‚Äôt help but feel that this was a huge step down from the original. 
I‚Äôm content with an ok/average sequel and I knew this wouldn‚Äôt beat the first, but damn, the standards are really low here unfortunately.

Jenkins is too obsessed with the Richard donner superman movies that were made to fit that cheesy, campy, lighthearted, demographic. It‚Äôs just a shame this movie emulated the tone of the last two reeve-superman movies that were mediocre at best. Having said that, I enjoyed Gal Gadot‚Äôs performance once again, she‚Äôs really hindered by a bad script but she certainly puts in 100% and I can‚Äôt fault her for that. 

Chris pine‚Äôs Steve is the hot topic of this movie; regardless of what you thought of his character this time around, I enjoyed it. Their chemistry is the heart of the movie. I liked Kristen wigg as Barbara, her character was way too flawed and predictable to be a credible threat, despite this, I enjoyed it for what it was. Die hard cheetah fans will be disappointed to know that she only appears as cheetah for one fight scene that lasts about 3 mins at best. And it‚Äôs a pretty underwhelming one at that. This was more of a bastardisation of the cheetah alter-ego, not the definitive take on the character. However in the context of this movie, she had more screen time than max!  Which brings me to Pedro pascal finally.


His talents are seriously under-utilised here but he chews up the scenery and makes the most of his performance. Thankfully, his final scene (with his son) was perhaps the most emotionally charged moment in the entire movie and a definitive one at that. His character had a sound resolution to an otherwise forgettable-ridiculous-OTT-villain in a terribly written story. 

This felt so episodic, lacking that cinematic feel of the original, here‚Äôs hoping we can move on and dive deeper into themyscira and Diana‚Äôs Olympian heritage much more next time. In fact, more time spent on her world and less on earth would be a welcome change that the franchise will benefit from in future.

I honestly feel that your disappointment in the movie isn't because it is a bad movie. I enjoyed it. It's not one of my "Will watch multiple times in the next month" movies (Cough cough....., Winter Soldier) but it's definitely not a bad movie.

I feel you probably had an idea as to what you wanted the movie to be like but it wasn't that. And that's not necessarily a bad thing.

It was a story about Diana. Not about the stone. Not about Cheetah. Not about Maxwell Lord. Not about Trevor or the random guy he displaced. It was about DIANA. Her weakness and growth.

Cheetah isn't so much an antagonist as she is a mirror. Without Cheetah, Diana doesn't recognize what she is becoming by holding on to Trevor. By choosing to "take the shortcut" rather than do what is right.

Trevor is her ultimate weakness. He is the thing she desires above all else. Giving him up when she could keep him is the ultimate Superhero act. What else could they bring as precious that would carry as much weight.???.
While I was also kinda disturbed by the whole Trevor taking up some generic Hallmark Christmas movie guy's life, it makes sense the more I think about it.
Conservation of energy states that you can not create or destroy energy. So the stone couldn't drop a whole new person into this universe from nowhere. It had to use the energy and mass available within this universe. üòäüòäüòä
But more in line with the story, you see how greed and selfishness don't just innocently give you what you want but take from others. By bringing Trevor back Diana takes the random generic Hallmark Christmas movie dude away from his family and friends. She's robbing others of what is theirs to get what she wants. Kinda like how that Egyptian dude who asked for his land back not only lost his security but also denied others their source of water.

The wishes didn't just cost the one making the wish but everyone else as well.

It's a story about Diana's selfishness and greed. It's a story about the selfishness and greed of all of us.

If you were looking for explosions and fight sequences and senseless violence, you'll definitely be disappointed. If you watched it wanting to be told a story, a good, classic story that you'll probably watch with family and friends later on. Then you'll probably like it.

Okay so, something very interesting I personally found with my two times viewing this film, that I'd love if you guys thought about:
My first time viewing it, I was horribly let down. I didn't like it, I almost hated it, and I thought it was the worst DC movie to have come out till now.
However, what I realised was that I went in viewing it as a direct sequel to the first, which I don't think is what the point of the movie was in the first place. That is when I sat back and thought about what Patty Jenkins wanted to say and show us. A completely distinct and whole new independent adventure, with its own philosophical crisis, and a completely new path for Wonder Woman to take in terms of her growth.
So when I rewatched it, I went in with the sole goal of seeing what Patty wanted to show us...¬†
And I loved it.
Let me explain:
I think that I had previously gotten too caught up with things such as a lack of action, a lack of Cheetah, and just an overall movie that lacked compelling aspects to it. However, this time, not only did I appreciate the tonal change that Patty put in to pay homage to Lynda Carter's WW, the one most of us grew up with and loved (I appreciated it what what is was this time), but more importantly, I saw Diana for the struggles she was silently dealing with, and how her love for humanity, a love that she would be willing to put everything else aside for, stood in complete opposition to Maxwell Lord, who is the direct opposite. And I loved how this rivalry in philosophies played out in the end.
And the fact that there was not a crazy end-all fight scene in the end may have been a let down at first, but then I realised and appreciated the fact that to Patty, it is less about physical fighting, it is more about the spiritual and philosophical strife that Wonder Woman stands for. THAT is what WW is about.
Even in terms of loopholes, I found many of them answered this time while watching it.
Overall, all I would like to say is that what DC is about is giving directors a chance to tell stories and make art. And I love respecting that. And I really think that everyone should definitely rewatch it, keeping in mind that this is its own thing, and it should perhaps be given a chance to be appreciated for that.
Anyway, my perspective on this movie has completely changed, and I really like it now. Sure, it won't stand close to the first, in terms of so many things; but, to me, that does not in any way take away from this film itself, neither should it.
Please rewatch it if you can, that is all I want to suggest. I really like it now, and I hope you do too!

(SPOILER ALERT)  A QUICK GUIDE IN UNDERSTANDING THE NARRATIVE OF 'WONDER WOMAN 1984':

TRUTH VS. LIES
To summarize WONDER WOMAN 1984, it's simply TRUTH vs LIES, and we see that at the beginning & ending of the film.  Patty Jenkins on Twitter said that the first Wonder Woman movie was about being "brave enough to LOVE" while this second film is about being "brave enough to face the TRUTH."  This second installment brings the other side of the warrior Wonder Woman, and that is being a peacemaker.  Patty Jenkins forgoes with the warrior's sword & shield so our attention will be on the peacemaker's Lasso of Hestia a.k.a. the Lasso of TRUTH which is the key to the undoing of the magical wish-fulfilling McGuffin of the Dreamstone of LIES.  

BE CAREFUL WHAT YOU WISH FOR 'CUZ YOU'LL NEVER KNOW WHAT YOU GET
When Diana wished for Steve's return, a lot of people took issue on how she got him back, that is, him being in another person's body.  The idea of this twist is that it should be surprising, and the film effectively got the surprise reaction (albeit divisive) from its audience it intended to draw.  Just like at Steve's return, Diana was as surprise as Barbara was surprise with the perks of being "like Diana"‚Äîlike the old man was surprise where the farm he wished for was located which is in the city.  It is clear that the Dreamstone doesn't automatically exact the wisher's wish, like it knows what their specific desire & intent upon making their wish.  Note that Diana has not gotten over Steve and is forlorn for quite sometime, that upon Steve's "most unusual return," she'll take it, although she'd most rather have him back fully in his own body.  Because Steve has been long gone, we can presume that the magic of the Dreamstone has limitations in resurrecting the absolutely dead.  The best that the McGuffin can do was to conjure the rested soul of Steve and have him exchange places with another person's soul, inhabiting that person's living body while the other person spends time in the "good place" (heaven?) Steve was before he found himself in the random person's futon bed. 

THE INVISIBLE JET
Never mind how Diana "wondrously" Gandalf her way in Themyscira-izing a modern jet plane (we get it that she's the daughter of Zeus, plus she's not called "Wonder" Woman for nothing)...The bigger question here is, how Steve was able to fly it?  This is a no issue for those who have carefully watched the first Wonder Woman film.  In that movie, Steve Trevor was able to fly (to his death) a humongous Nazi plane he called "the future."  He called it "the future" because it was a way more advanced in technology than the planes they had at that time.  If he was able to fly that aircraft, then it's easy for him to figure out the modern "invisible jet" plane being a pilot himself with good knowledge in how aerodynamics work.      

NOT QUITE A "HEAVEN CAN'T WAIT" RETURN
Movie writers  doesn't always cater to every moviegoer's likes and dislikes pertaining to how they wanted the direction of the film's story is going, and writers are free to set the rules they want for the premise of their story they're trying to convey to work, and then they just have to cross their fingers and hope the movie's audience are intelligent enough to understand the narrative they're trying to tell.  As for this particular divisive movie, in as much as half of its audience prefer to rather have Steve come back fully (body & soul) in the most conventional & convenient way avoiding controversy (the issue of without-consent body swapping), we on the contrary prefer the filmmakers' bold choice of having him back this twisted way‚Äîunconventional, inconvenient & not clich√©.  Quite original we might say, albeit very contentious understandably.  All for that pivotal heartbreaking letting-you-go moment of Steve and Diana.  That scene wouldn't have worked the way that it did if the storytellers went the easy way...
     DIANA: "I can't say goodbye...I can't say goodbye..."
     STEVE: "You don't have to...I'm already gone."
Those lines would have been not impactful at all if they did it differently...And NO, we don't want an AVENGERS: INFINITY WAR all over again, where we see a fully-resurrected Steve Trevor fade away or poofed out of existence‚Äîthat would have been a far worse awful thing than the "disastrous cringey twist" haters of the movie are nitpicking!  It's vital for the movie to show that Diana needs to face the TRUTH that Steve has long been gone from her life, that she's kidding herself if she intends to keep Steve in this most unusual way‚Äîthat things should go back to its proper order especially for that Lyle Waggoner-looking "handsome guy" who she‚Äîout of being forlorn for the longest time‚Äîunintentionally used conveniently like a crutch to heal her broken heart.  Yes, it's not easy to be Diana‚Äîto be a demigoddess‚Äîto be immortal who loves immortally.  Immortal Love‚Äîhave you heard of it?  Well, the daughter of Zeus suffers from a bad case of this Immortal Love‚Äîblame it on her god side.  If Diana wants to continue to be our beloved Wonder Woman, she needs to "man" up in accepting her own flaws‚Äîto stay in touch with her human side so she can be "brave enough to face the TRUTH."  As Antiope once said to her, "TRUTH is all there is...No true hero is born from LIES."  And what's the main TRUTH of the matter here?  That humans are mortal, and gods & goddesses live on.  Steve is human and he died a long time ago.  Diana needs to accept this undeniable TRUTH of hers that she's been dodging for so-sooooo long, and move on with her immortal life‚Äîso she could continue on being our beloved superhero, Wonder Woman‚Äîflaws and all.

APEX PREDATOR
There are beautiful juxtapositions in this movie.  One mentioned is TRUTH vs LIES‚Äîthe Lasso of TRUTH vs the Dreamstone of LIES.  Another is Wonder Woman vs the Cheetah.  It was a smart move of Patty Jenkins & company to throw Wonder Woman's Golden Eagle armor in the mix.  It gave us the visual spectacle of the jungle element wherein we see the battle of two apex predators‚Äîthe eagle and the wildcat.  Barbara Minerva, knowing now that her wish to be "like Diana" makes her just of equal footing with the Amazon princess, wished to be more than be "like Diana"‚Äîso she asked to be "unlike any other"‚Äîsomebody unbeatable like an apex predator above the food chain.  And as we have discussed, the Dreamstone does not exact the wisher's wish, so be careful what you wish for.     

FIGURE OF SPEECH
Now regarding those PARTICLES with Maxwell Lord touching wishers with them, it really takes an intelligent attentive movie audience to get the angle.  The new tech Global Broadcast Satellite, uses PARTICLE beam technology just like the Star Wars program, as the POTUS explained, "It bathes the landscape in a signal of PARTICLES that goes in and fiddles with any technology it TOUCHES."  Max caught the POTUS' word "TOUCHES," and so he thought he would be able to "TOUCH" every viewer the satellite is broadcasting to, making it possible for him to do his global wish-granting.  He asked the POTUS, "You said 'TOUCHES'?  As in the PARTICLES you are sending are touching everything?"  And the POTUS, bewildered to where Max was going with this, answered, "It's a FIGURE OF SPEECH but yes.  That's how it was explained to me."  We can see here that the whole Global Broadcast Satellite technology was understood vaguely by the POTUS as a "FIGURE OF SPEECH," unsure himself that it really works that way, but Max Lord understood it differently, thinking and believing that it would work the way he thought that it might work.  But did this new Star Wars program-like satellite technology really work as Max Lord understood it?  The answer is NO.  The "technological PARTICLES" was not really at work here as it was just really a FIGURE OF SPEECH, it was fully magic.  It was just advance technological satellite taking over others' broadcasting globally.  What made it work was when that soldier in charge of the bunker wished it would work as Maxwell Lord deemed the whole thing to work.  Recall that scene and you will understand.  Simply put, Max, the human Dreamstone went from "TOUCH MODE" to "SAY MODE" when that soldier wished the whole thing would work for Lord.  Most people didn't get this.  As we have said, it takes an intelligent viewer of the film to get it.

THE MANDELA EFFECT
So what happened after the magical event that took place in 1984?  Does anyone at present time in this universe (DCEU) remember what took place then?  Vaguely‚Äîeveryone is not sure about the whole event like how the U.S. President was confused about him being in the White House when he seem to remember being somewhere else.  What resulted from this magical event somehow caused a MANDELA-like EFFECT on the masses.

I actually enjoyed the movie, although I was not so interested in the romantic subplot between Diana and Steve, but the relationship grew on me a little, and I understood in the grand context of the movie why it was utilized. The story‚Äôs message in that moment was highlighting the difference between want and need, quite literally in the context of this movie.
And I found the dialogue scene between Diana and Barbara when they were talking about the stone to be really funny, when you considered the stone to be phallic symbolism, instead of a MacGuffin, which gives off a real lesbian vibe between Diana and Barbara, which I found interesting, especially when you consider Maxwell Lord to be part of this love triangle.
And I liked how Jenkins gave the main villains an actual character; Barbara wants to be a dominating force in her life, similar to Lord, each wanting control over their own lives, which is an interesting theme that they explored in the movie. 
Overall, I enjoyed the film, although like Chris himself, I was wondering what impact this event would have on the culture of the world in the DCEU.

Tonally, this film was really jarring, particularly as a sequel.

The first film seemed like modern era comics- more "grounded", New 52 style tone. It had to prove that Wonder Woman could stand toe-to-toe w/ any other superhero.

This film, on the other hand, felt more Silver Age. It had some cheese & goofiness.

On paper, & for reasons you pointed out, I should've been really disappointed. The tonal whiplash should be like watching Batman Begins then Batman & Robin.
But... 
...I kinda liked it? Like I _really_ enjoyed WW84. I loved the way they just embraced shit like Aquaman. 

I'm not saying there aren't any flaws [every movie has issues, even our favorite "perfect" films]. But I'm just saying that... for me at least, I loved it & plan to watch again. Though I'm curious what a 3rd film could be like now. 
Which tone will it aim for? Or will it go a new way again?

It makes me sad since I have been a huge Wonder Woman fan my whole life. This film could've used one of her storylines from the comics, but instead they did their own thing and it was a terrible plot. They also did Steve dirty and Cheetah too. Don't even get me started on her portrayal, they totally ruined her and the fight was terrible. The only good things about the film that should've stayed (while everything else should have been different) was the opening scene, the post credits scene, and Pedro Pascal and Gal Gadot's acting. Wish they would've gotten a good script with a good story. They could've adapted The Circle storyline or the Bana Mighdall storyline or the storyline where Diana decides to find Themyscira meanwhile Veronica Cale's daughter is kidnapped by Two evil Gods Phobos and Deimos and they blackmail her into doing their bidding, to help them find Themyscira, including bringing monsters from the dead for WW to fight and funding an expedition for Diana's friend Barbara Ann Minerva who wants to help her find more Gods (and Themyscira) to go to the safari in Africa where Phobos and Deimos force her to undertake a ritual where she becomes the host of Cheetah, an African Goddess of the Hunt who existed before written language and was a guardian for a tribe. If they could have cast Rebecca Ferguson or Rebecca Leigh Madder as Barbara Ann, gave her storyline and character more depth like she has in the comics, showed her becoming Cheetah in the second act and being a ferocious monster who eats people and rips out hearts and if they could've used motion capture picture (like the Avatar movie) and a better design to actually make Cheetah look good. They should've modeled her look after the Injustice 2 design. As for having Steve return, that should've happened in modern day so that he didn't have to die again (so the movie should've taken place after JL) (and had a flashback scene with the lasso to show a montage of Diana's life between the two movies). Instead of having him come back because of a wish (and possessing a freaking body! Wtf were the writers thinking?!) Diana could have gone on an archeological trip Indiana Jones and Mummy style where she found the portal to Elysium (Heaven in a Greek Mythology) and went in to briefly reunite with Antiope and Steve who decides to return with her. Then he could have come back to life in the flesh and in the WW1 clothes he died in (which would've gotten him funny looks) then he and Diana could have went to a store where he hilariously tries on a bunch of clothes until he finds a modern outfit he likes. Then he could've been in the movie working and fighting with her and being her confident about the new mysterious Cheetah God and Diana's anguish when she finds out the God is Barbara. During the movie he and Diana should have been selfless trying to help people and be heroic, but finally get to be happy together at the end. If they adapted the storyline with Veronica Cale and Cheetah the film could have come closer to its climax after Diana, Veronica, Cheetah, and Steve find Themyscira and have a confrontation with Phobos and Deimos. Either Veronica could have been redeemed and ended up staying on Themyscira with her daughter or she could have suffered the consequences she did in the comics where she finds out that her daughter has to stay on Themyscira in order to stay whole and leaves sad because she can't take her daughter back with her and gets into legal trouble due to other crimes, gets away with it, but is still miserable because she is without her daughter which is karma for hurting so many people on her quest to find her with no remorse. Personally I would have loved it if they went with that storyline and had Veronica be redeemed and desire to join her daughter on Themyscira. Then for Cheetah to disappear and Diana tells Steve she is going after her (or for Cheetah to be presumed dead) Diana thinks she's dead and mourns her lost, but it is revealed that she is still alive and is bringing the Gods and several monsters back to life. Then the movie could've ended with Diana and Steve returning home discussing how he will have to get a new identity and they reunite happy together for the first time thinking about themselves ready to have more time together. The movie should have had a way better fight choreographer and the action should've been better. Diana should've kept her sword and shield. The movie also should have explained Diana's powers and why the Amazons are immortal. They are immortal because of the water in their island being from The Fountain of Youth and Diana's powers came from her being a demigod, but when a God kills a God they take their powers and mantle, so when WW killed Ares, she took all the powers and mantles he took from the other Gods. She could have used the lasso to show Barbara a montage of her life (a montage could've showed Etta and Charlie's wedding, Diana's friends from the first movie getting old and dying Diana fighting in WW2 and killing Hitler, then in the 50's or 60's she found Harmonia's Amunlet (an important item from the comics) which transported her to another world and for years she was in a magical world where she met other Gods and Monsters and had to kill a few of them, and she was trapped in that world until she returned to it in the year 1984 where she met Julia Kapatelis, daughter of an Amazon Diana knew on Themyscira who apparently left after she did and Diana moved in with Julia and her daughter Vanessa and they filled the hole in her heart that losing her first friends in our world left. For years she fought in her costume, fast enough so nobody saw and every sighting of her became a legend that some people believe in (due to witnesses) and some people don't. Until she decided to put her armor back on to help fight Doomsday. Ever since, she made her presence known to the world and is being a hero in the open, but like in the book Spirit of Truth some people are afraid of her and don't trust her yet). Anyway all of that should have been a montage to show her life between the two movies and make it fit with DC continently. They also could have adapted the Eyes of the Gorgon storyline. The movie should have had better CGI, better action, a better choreographer,  more action then it did, better casting choice and look for Cheetah, and a better script. Any fan of WW comics knows that Geoff Johns CANNOT write Diana. He does a terrible job at that. Patty Jenkins is really kind and sweet. She's awesome and I love her as a person, but I don't know what she was thinking when she decided to have Geoff Johns, notorious amount WW fans be a co writer. She should've hired the screenwriter from the first film and Greg Rucka and another good screenwriter to write it. The genre of the movie should've been Fantasy/adventure and Superhero. I feel like I'm one of the few people who really liked this film. Although, I can't argue with many of the issues you flagged. 

It is weird that neither Diana nor Steve mentioned that a big reason for renouncing her wish was the - presumably - innocent man whose life was stolen. And, I honestly am more confused thinking about whether Diana could *actually* SEE original Steve, or not. In the moment, my head canon said yes. With her 'god' powers, and knowing who he was she was able to look past his outer 'shell' and see Steve. Like seeing the hidden image in one of those abstract posters. I'm also seriously confused about what the wish rules were when Pedro Pascal's character took back his wish. Wouldn't Cheetah still have her first set of powers? She got those before Pedro became the rock. 

So, why did I like it so much? For the same reason I watched the new Star Wars trilogy. I was there for the love story. Gadot's and Pine's on-screen chemistry zinged. And, I say this with respect, Gadot has clearly been working on her craft. I thought she was delightful to watch. And really felt for her in the end. 

I also enjoyed the extra serving of ham that Pascal and Wig served up. Unlike Electro, I didn't cringe through their scenes. But, looked forward to them. This is a film that could have been better. I couldn't believe how long it was, for example. But, I'm glad I saw this and found that the whole film was watchable. Unfortunately, I thought the second half of the first film was pretty terrible. Like an A student failing the final exam. If rather a B student who performs consistently.

I feel it's unfair that you spent 50%+ of this review comparing this movie to other movies.  While I agree that the script lacked a lot in specific areas, it's unfair to compare this to Superman 2 or the Incredible Hulk.  It was done 3-4 decades later and meant to be done in that same 80s tone (poorly, for the most part I admit, but see my comment below about editing), but you also never discussed that being Patty's intention in your review.  By the way, Spiderman 2 has a bunch of continuity errors if you really wanna be nit-picky.  Also, the "not taking a shortcut theme" was reinforced with each of the 3 main characters.  All of them took a shortcut (wish) to get what they wanted, and they all paid a price for it, albeit Cheetah the least noticeably.

I feel it is similar to B vs S and Justice League, where you'll find, after the fact, that much of what made it coherent was left on the editing room floor.   The "Quantum Leap" aspect of Steve's story was jarring, but the way Kristen Wiig played her role was fantastic, and Pedro Pascal was everything you wanted/expected from an 80s villain (barring the stupid, BS particle theory thing, which kinda works as an 80s trope).  The storyline was disjointed, but the acting was spot on, especially when you realize it was meant to be an "80s movie," you appreciate certain aspects better.   

All in all, I blame the editing and really feel we need a "Patty Jenkins cut" to see what this movie really should've been.  I give it a B.  I enjoyed it despite having so many plot issues.  This coming from a Marvel fanboy, except DC's animated movies kick ass.

Plot was nearly the same as the first one. Drenched in oversaturated cgi, and more upsetting it looked like what a 12 year old thinks the year 1984 actually looked like. Everything from the Clich√©d fashion, the cars, building designs, didn't exist in the 1984 I remember. And that stupid fucking scene where they steal a stored jet fighter from what is basically a museum was somehow fully fuelled and ready to go. Oddly, the museum for retired aircraft had a manned aircraft control tower and full security to chase a fighter jet down a runway at an airport that doesn't have any flights because ITS A MUSEUM. Not to mention, they flew overseas, and across continental Africa to Egypt without having to hit up a few air-to-air refueling tankers along the way. In reality that jet would have ditched 500 kms off the eastern seaboard when it ran out of fuel. Maybe it ran efficiently on biofuel made from bullshit. Okay so, something very interesting I personally found with my two times viewing this film, that I'd love if you guys thought about:
My first time viewing it, I was horribly let down. I didn't like it, I almost hated it, and I thought it was the worst DC movie to have come out till now.
However, what I realised was that I went in viewing it as a direct sequel to the first, which I don't think is what the point of the movie was in the first place. That is when I sat back and thought about what Patty Jenkins wanted to say and show us. A completely distinct and whole new independent adventure, with its own philosophical crisis, and a completely new path for Wonder Woman to take in terms of her growth.
So when I rewatched it, I went in with the sole goal of seeing what Patty wanted to show us...¬†
And I loved it.
Let me explain:
I think that I had previously gotten too caught up with things such as a lack of action, a lack of Cheetah, and just an overall movie that lacked compelling aspects to it. However, this time, not only did I appreciate the tonal change that Patty put in to pay homage to Lynda Carter's WW, the one most of us grew up with and loved (I appreciated it what what is was this time), but more importantly, I saw Diana for the struggles she was silently dealing with, and how her love for humanity, a love that she would be willing to put everything else aside for, stood in complete opposition to Maxwell Lord, who is the direct opposite. And I loved how this rivalry in philosophies played out in the end.
And the fact that there was not a crazy end-all fight scene in the end may have been a let down at first, but then I realised and appreciated the fact that to Patty, it is less about physical fighting, it is more about the spiritual and philosophical strife that Wonder Woman stands for. THAT is what WW is about.
Even in terms of loopholes, I found many of them answered this time while watching it.
Overall, all I would like to say is that what DC is about is giving directors a chance to tell stories and make art. And I love respecting that. And I really think that everyone should definitely rewatch it, keeping in mind that this is its own thing, and it should perhaps be given a chance to be appreciated for that.
Anyway, my perspective on this movie has completely changed, and I really like it now. Sure, it won't stand close to the first, in terms of so many things; but, to me, that does not in any way take away from this film itself, neither should it.
Please rewatch it if you can, that is all I want to suggest. I really like it now, and I hope you do too!

A flight from Egypt to D.C. is 12 hours and 9 minutes.

So we see Diana and Steven commandeer (steal) a plane from an airport clearly at night. They took a taxi to get there.
Which then means they took a 12 hour flight to Egypt, arriving there at 3pm.

So after Max Lord visited that Oil Tycoon in Egypt and granted him his wish and then Diana and Steve confronted Max on the roadway trying to stop him, we saw Barbara on the phone in her office talking to Diana in Egypt where it was midday there (in Egypt) and people around her were working as well in their offices in D.C. and we saw daylight shining through in Barbara's office when she was on the phone with Diana.

Obviously this is possible because lets say all that happened in Egypt around 4pm. (an hour after Diana and Steve landed in Egypt; heck maybe even 5pm in Egypt since the Sun sets there around 7pm anyway in July, so lets give them a 2 hour window for that whole Egypt fight scene) then it would have been 9 (or 10) in the morning in Washington D.C.  So that part we can assume to be legit.

Then we cut to Barbara Minerva at the record store in D.C. when Diana and Steve show up (the next day) and she says 'that was fast' which was met by Diana's 'Good morning', indicating that it was morning sometime in D.C. 

So in order for Diana and Steve to arrive in Washington DC in the morning the next day, they would have had to leave Cairo Egypt by plane by 2am, which would have been 7pm in D.C., aka still the 'same day' for Barbara who had spoken to them earlier on the phone, which then would have resulted in Diana and Steve showing up in Washington D.C. arriving at the airport at 7am, then possibly meeting up with Barbara at the record store around 8am hence Diana saying 'good morning' after Barbara said "that was fast".

So yeah its confusing but its actually possible.
The only leap of logic would be that the fighter plane, normally showcased for museum archives was fuel prepped for a 12 hour flight

Just saw the movie after waiting for two years. It could have been better, here are my thoughts: While I watched it, I loved the open sequence. I had fun while watching the movie and enjoyed it, however it was a majorly flawed film and I can see why so many people dislike it. There are eight things I wish the film had done differently to make it better‚Ä¶
1. Steve Trevor should've come back in the flesh, not possessing a body. Not only was having possession disturbing and problematic, but it was also stupid.  Not to mention that poor guy! Where is he? Will he lost his job? Steve had sex with Diana in another body. WHY?! They could have just had Steve come back AS STEVE! Here's how it could have happened: Remember that awkward guy who knew Diana and worked in Washington? Who tried asking her out at the party? He could have asked her if she had a boyfriend and Diana could have told him she had someone, lost him, and that she wished she had more time with him. Then she could have walked away from him, then heard Steve‚Äôs voice say, ‚ÄúDiana.‚Äù Then she could have turned around...and saw Steve Trevor in the flesh! In the outfit he died in. Then he could have stayed the night at her apartment and then they could have gone to a store (where he looked out of place in his WW1 clothes) then had the funny scene where he tried on a bunch of eighties outfits in a store.
2. Barbara Minerva/Cheetah should've been portrayed by Rebecca Leigh Madder or Rebecca Ferguson. They are both redheads, British, and have the range to pull off Cheetah as an antagonist.
3. Some of the dialogue could have been tweaked. For example, at the mall Diana could have said, ‚Äúreally, you still think guns will work on me?‚Äù Instead of ‚ÄúI hate guns.‚Äù And Regan could've said, ‚Äúoh my God‚Äù instead of ‚Äúwe‚Äôve fired for less.‚Äù
4. The pacing near the end was awful and should have been changed. That last scene with Max Lord before he decided to save his son and renounce his wish did not have to be dragged on.
5. Cheetah‚Äôs origins could have been more faithful. While I loved her development. How she went from being awkward and relatable and wanting to be like Diana, to slowly becoming more confident, then eventually cold and selfish. They could have had Max send her on an expedition to the Safari in Africa where she and a small crew come across a tribe and they could have done the ritual from the comics that caused her to become the host of an ancient African Cat Goddess who existed before written language.
6. Cheetah should have looked different. They should've done what James Cameron did to Zoe Saladona in Avatar and modeled her design after Cheetah in Injustice 2 and they should have shown her fight Diana as Cheetah before their final fight. I would have liked to see her have Ginger Snaps moments of eating people. They could have at least showed her ripping out someone's heart and earring it, like she once did in the comics. They also should have revealed that she is still the host of a Goddess at the end and is now immortal like Diana.
7. They should have got a better action director because the final fight sucked.
8. There should have been more action!

Honestly, the storyline could have revolved around Diana trying to stop the Cold War instead of a wish stone. After watching Chris Struckmann's review, I realized that it is convoluted. Plus Diana could have taken away people's memories of the events. They should have showed the villains suffering consequences.

Now there were some things I did like about the movie. I thought Pedro Pascal and Gal Gadot had great performances. I thought Max and Barbara had good character development and sympathetic moments. I liked Max as a villain. Nowadays a lot of people want things without working to earn it. I catch myself being that way and thought Max‚Äôs story showed why our society and my generation need to be less lazy and entitled. I loved the opening scene on Themyscira with the Amazon Olympics and Antiope teaching Diana about honesty. Usually I prefer dark or gritty or a balance between darkness and light heartedness, but I actually liked how campy it was and the aesthetics of the film. It was very 80‚Äôs and made me feel nostalgic for 80‚Äôs films. It was fun! The camera work was great and I liked the score because it fit the movie. I liked the jokes and funny lines, they landed for me. I was so happy that they showed pictures of Diana‚Äôs friends from the first film that showed wedding pictures of Etta and Charlie (I ship it) and the picture of Diana with Etta as an old lady. I loved the Lynda Carter scene, that it was revealed that she was the Amazon warrior who originally had the golden armor. Now the film was flawed and could have been miles better. I understand why so many people hate it, but I like that I was able to turn off my brain during the movie and have mindless fun. Of course it would have been more fun if the third act and last fight scene were better, but the first two acts were a blast for me.

Please don't attack me or cuss at me for having a different opinion. I liked the movie, but really hated some things about it that almost ruined the movie for me (Steve‚Äôs possession, the way they handled Cheetah, the pacing near the end, etc.) I understand why some people hate the film and why some people like it. We are all entitled to our own opinions, so let's keep it civil. To me, the opening sequence and the first 20 minutes was the best part!

Seemed like a movie script that was for a different movie, then repurposed as a Wonder Woman movie. Also, there were a lot of unexplained plot holes.
-They just find a plane that is fully fueled and ready to go? Also, that type of plane can't fly that far without refuelling.
-Turning the whole plane invisible while only having practiced on a coffee cup before? And she did it when she was supposed to be losing her powers?
-Flying back from Africa to the USA in one day in the same plane?
-Her powers seem highly inconsistent when fighting the military vehicles. One moment she is kicking big vehicles all over the place, then next she is almost crushed by one.
-Her boyfriend acts like he's never seen trains before, or fireworks. He's not from the stone age.
-Every human on earth is selfish and only make selfish wishes. Then they all regret it and take their wish back. Humans of the earth are not a hive mind.
-The villain could have easily stopped Wonder Woman. He could just have one of his guards wish her dead, or at least wish her to be sent to the other side of the world.
-Some people can make outlandish wishes, like will thousands of nuclear weapons into existence. But Wonder Woman can't wish her boyfriend back from the dead in his own body? Instead it's some poor guy that is taken over by him. She also uses his body physically without his consent, as the body's real mind doesn't have a say in the matter.
-Cheeta gets to make two wishes for some reason, while the movie clearly states that that's not possible.
-The movie doesn't explain why Max is getting sick. Why is he getting sick?
-Max's kid made a wish, but nothing came of it.
Honestly speaking, the trama of a wishing stone, even for this seems to be lazy writing. Super convenient how the movie went.

I will never be one to decry Gal Gadot being on screen esp in her Wonder Woman guise, but this movie tried TOO hard to be so sentimental and message oriented that it forget to be a superhero action film.  Also, Covid-19 really messed up their filming and editing resulting in some rather bizarre narrative jumps. Speaking of jumps...Wonder Woman can lasso a lightning bolt which is an electric discharge between the atmosphere and the ground? It would be easier lasso a raindrop than lightning. That said...we're in the realm of beings who can shoot lasers out of their eyes and freeze item with their super breath so whatever! 

The movie while entertaining never quite seems to define its objective.  The audience is left wondering what exactly Diana is doing in 1984.  Why is she still pining for Steve someone who died some 63 to 66 years ago.  Diana seems less forlorn about having left Themyscira, where she lived since birth, never to be able to return there than losing Steve whom she had known for at most a week or so.  Fine...so goes the story.  She misses Steve and somehow gets him back but only in a really weird way that displaces another person entirely.  This is something that Diana should NOT be okay with.  

In that way WW 1984 is more about how our moral nature gets corrupted by pursuing the unreal...to have the return of someone who has died, to suddenly go from boring to breathtaking, nearly invisible to absolutely irresistible (btw Kristen Wiig is NOT the person to portray/pull off such a transformation), to suddenly regain lost kingdoms and instantaneous rags to riches, military stalemate to dominance etc.  It's about how our desire for shortcuts or circumventing of the "rules" produces untold and unforeseen consequences which we should NOT be okay with.  Our riches cannot come at impoverishing others, our strength cannot come through rendering others weak, our cups cannot runeth over as others' cups are emptied.  THIS moral lesson could have been told with finer finesse and more nuanced narration than what we got, but at least it tried.  

On the topic of male boorishness which the WW 1984 did not shy away from, the movie was far to obvious and heavy-handed in depicting this.  Instead of revealing such classless crassness in SOME male characters through poignant specific events, the movie opted for pervasiveness and frequency rather than one or two vivid, intense examples.  And the movie really failed to weave this particular thread into the rest of the overall narrative tapestry. In that way, WW 1984 felt choppy and discoherent.

WW84 is nowhere near the quality of the first Wonder Woman movie unfortunately.  The story turns into a big, silly mess by the end and it really just loses me.  I just keep realizing I'm watching a bad movie at some point late in the film.  The first portion of the movie was good.  The childhood flashback was great.  The mall scene had cute moments, albeit the action seemed a bit out-of-flow/odd.  Too much bad CGI, but I liked the character interaction and the acting, so I dismissed the odd/over-done special effects.  

The story writing is just.....bad....no, TERRIBLE.....because I guessed what Diana's wish was and what would end up happening with the artifact the moment Diana wished on it casually.  I literally guessed the entire movie in that moment and it was a childishly easy guess.   So, the writing is fitting only for a child, which is okay because it's a comic-book movie.  

What I didn't think worked was the final 45 mins where the story just became a convoluted muck of overlapping quandaries and sidetracking nonsense.  I got a massive headache from the amount of 'dumb' the story deteriorated into.  The flow was bad in the most important portions of the movie.  I found that I enjoyed the romantic parts of the movie more than the  action, and I'm a man.....so, it translates that Chris Pine pretty much saved the movie with his parts and his great chemistry with the lead actress.  

Anyways, that's my review.  A "D+" grade.  It was below average, but watchable because at least one of the sub-plots, the romance, worked and wasn't cheesy.

I liked this film. Didn't rock my world. But I don't think it's a waste of time. I agree with you on the runtime. What I truly think we have here is a case of the trailer having dropped too long ago. People had a lot of time to decide what the film was going to be and build up expectations. And having now seen the film, the trailer in a way - showed too much. Not that it was a "bad" trailer. But practically every action sequence in the film was featured in some way or another in the marketing campaign of the film. Meaning that the only material not really featured in any of the trailers were the so-called "character scenes". Which by and large is where I felt this film fell a bit flat. Diana's isolation post-Steve's death has honestly been done a bit to death at this point. Literally every single time she shows up in one of these movies it's a montage of: "Gal Gadot in a fabulous outfit looking sad because dead boyfriend."

I think it was a huge mistake to show Chris Pine in the trailers. Because that would actually have been a nice twist. I also felt myself wishing for just a little more groundwork on both the Barbara and the Maxwell Lord characters. Establish them as SUCH losers first, that their literal willingness to watch the world burn JUST so they can have whatever they want.....would be more established. I don't think they did a completely piss poor job of this. I just would have appreciated one or two more scenes. Instead of JUST showing the attempted rape and rescue; show Barbara eating alone in the lunchroom day after day, and in then eating dinner alone night after night in an empty apartment that's littered with Cat paraphernalia. We got one scene of her greeting a few people and having them not talk back to her, and then Diana shows up and they become friends. I didn't FEEL her utter desperation to be noticed the way I would've if the plot and pacing of the film would've allowed for us to just spend a bit more time with her. As for Maxwell Lord, I don't think they established him as enough of a loser. Yes we get the whole ponzy scheme scene. But instead of a disgruntled investor, I would've appreciated his son's mother, or maybe a parent being super disappointed in what he's become. Maybe even a phone message from a wife in the process of leaving him, or a divorce attorney advising him on the latest one. I'm possibly nitpicking, but given how much time the film devotes to their downfall post wish; I think it would have been nice to sympathize with the state of their lives before.

Wonder Woman hits all the marks it intended to. It is a well made thoughtful and entertaining movie. Only today I had commented about super hero movies either choosing to put a concept or a character at the fore front. Wonder Woman brilliantly puts both together and gives a viewer a sequel that beats the original which itself is rare and achievement. With an interesting story that has familiar elements WW84 brick by brick and stone by stone (spoiler alert) takes the viewer to the final concept and the message at the heart of story. The major credit must go to the screen play and the script writer who show that you can tell an old story in a new way if you want to. They really ensure that viewer misses nothing and plot comes together at the end even though you spend a good 45 minutes building the story up. I mean what Wonder Woman manages to achieve in its narrative is outstanding given its main plot is grounded in fantasy and yet its idea is so contemporary and relevant to current world. The film also has great production designs, good acting very well used CGI and action sequences.  The film does have a few minor flaws and lacks the big confrontation between the super heroine and bad guy in the final sequence which we normally see in action movies. It takes some entertainment value  but allows the movie to deliver its message very emphatically. This is a well made movie and will rank among the top 10 super hero movies as time goes by. It will be remembered as it has emotional as well as intellectual depth.  A pat for Patty Jenkins and maybe expect a Oscar nomination as well. Gal Gadot is a vast improvement over her previous WW films and she truly acts the character maybe a supporting actor nomination for Max Lord. Well done. This was a complete surprise and way better than expectations.

It was alright.  It wasn't as much as it was hyped up to be, but I wouldn't consider it a complete failure.  I love Wonder Woman's character.  The movie had several technical issues; including the CGI, the pacing, and the direction of some points of the story.   I didn't know which character to focus on.  Also, I don't understand how anyone anticipated that the main villain would be anti Trump.  There's literally nothing about him that reminds me of Trump at all.  He's just like Jim Carey's character from Liar Liar with Trump's outer appearance, but that's it.  He's even redeemed by the end of the film.  My biggest issue with this film and some of the other DC movies is that, unlike the Marvel films, there's nothing added to the overall universe.  There isn't anything foreshadowed that we can look forward to in later films.  We didn't even see what happened to the crystal.  I also wished that we saw what the god of that stone looked like; that was one of my few disappointments.  When Maxwell started to break down from the wishes, I thought he was going to turn into that god. So just saw WW1984 personally I thought it was good but it's got some problems like any other movie. In terms of the divided fanbase, I think I understand why this is happening. It's the MoS argument all over again. The world was introduced to the Donner Superman and that version has stuck with the general population for many years.

When an edgier Superman was introduced in MoS, people rejected it and demanded they wanted the Donner archetype Superman since that's what most people have come to see Superman as; Happy, smiley guy who doesn't kill at least on the big screen.. I think the same situation has happened with WW1984. We were introduced to the edgy Amazon in BVS and WW but now we get a 180 version which by the way is still an accurate version of the character but not a version that most people expected or anticipated as even being a possibility for better and for worse.

I think WW1984 deserves a watch and hopefully viewers can understand that this is a true version of the character, albeit a different version but still a true version.
WW still tops my list but 84 does have good stuff in it.
